          <h3>Content and Characteristics</h3>
          <p>
            The text is diffiult. A 2000 year old text that reads more like a collection of quotes rather than as a comprehensive literary work (such as Plato's Apology) cannot help but be confusing. His sayings lack contextual elements, such as when, where, in what situation, in what way he imparted the saying to his disciples. Only the bare essences of his sayings remain (it doesn't help that books were painfully expensive and time-taking to create in the ancient times), and therefore it is difficult to decipher the exact meaning, although many scholars throughout history have tried.
          </p>
          <p>
            It does not help either that the ancient Chinese characters are vague (as they are more symbollic than semantic in meaning), which accounts for the many translations of even the damn title of the book accurately into English. 
          </p>
          <p>
            Unlike Plato's works which paint a portrait of Socrates' life and philosophies through a countinuous series of dialogue and events, the Analects is a collection of miscellaneous sayings collected from different disciples, which adds to the difficulty.
          </p>
          <p>
            Therefore, I have made an effort to 'modernize' many of his philosophies and written commentary on how I have perceived many of Confucian values and teachings in the present-day society. The interpretations presented are not to be taken as the most popular interpretations, or as commentary most relevant to Confucius' society at the time of writing the Analects. Read more about the <a href="/purpose">purpose</a> of the <a href="/">Noneo</a> to find out why I have decided to interpret such an ancient text.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="col-lg-6 col-md-6 col-sm-6">
          <img height="30%" width="60%" src="images/bamboo.png">
