          <h3>Chapters</h3>
          <p>
            The Noneo consists of 20 chapters. The title of the chapters do not signifiy the thematic elements of the chapter, but instead is just the first characters of the Chapters (excluding the well-known 'As Confucius said,' 子曰). I have taken effort to name the Chapters by their biggest thematic elements, to make the chapters more memorable and appealing to read.
          </p>
          <p>
            The first 10 chapters are commonly referred to as the "upper text", and the last 10 chapters as the "lower text". There is a notable distinction between the upper and lower texts, in terms of literary style and estimated dates of writing. The upper text is composed of passages that are short and brief, while the lower text is composed of passages that are long and wordy. Most historical estimates agree that the upper texts were written first, and have greater valilidity of actual Confucian teachings. For the purposes of the Noneo, there are valuable lessons and memorable quotes to be taken away from both the upper and lower texts equally.
          </p>
